    <text>
        <body>
            <div type=”letter”>
                <opener><dateline><date when="1915-05-13">May 13, 1915.</dateline></date>
                    <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute></opener>
                <p>I am sorry my letter made you sad. I am so attached to <title key="poetry" level="j">your paper</title> that perhaps I criticise it 
                    rather too freely sometimes, and certainly on insufficient data.</p>
                <p>Can’t you get more people to guarantee you money, if you are running behind — so much a year?
                    If you should think of doing this, I should be very glad to be one of your contributors to the
                    limit of my ability. I realize that a small circulation is a terrible bar to advertisements. 
                    Under those circumstances, you ought to have a large guarantee. If your present sum is not enough,
                    could it not be raised? At any rate, forgive me if I put my foot in it.</p>
                <p>By the way, I think <persName key="ac_henderson">Alice Henderson</persName> gave an entirely wrong idea of my opinion of <persName key="robert_frost">Frost</persName> by only
                    quoting one sentence and dwelling entirely on that. Frost came out to see me at once on receiving
                    his copy, to show there was no hard feeling; but I do object to being misrepresented by a <pb n="02">partial
                    quotation.</p>
                <closer>Sincerely yours,</closer>
                <!-- (break for signature) -->
                <p> Dictated but not signed by Miss Lowell.</p>
            </div>
